2829  ULONG ScsiPortCount; // Count of SCSI port adapters thus far
2830  ULONG SerialCount; // Count of serial devices thus far
2831  ULONG ParallelCount; // Count of parallel devices thus far

2835  // spaces that are used by WD1003-compatible disk controllers.

2839  BOOLEAN AtDiskSecondaryAddressClaimed; // 0x170 - 0x17F

2876 //

2878 // for the storage that they allocate on behalf of user file handles,
2879 // so the following amount of additional quota is charged against each

2888 // size of a FILE_OBJECT to get the actual charge amount.

4329  __irpSp->Control = 0; \

4560 
4561 //
4562 // Routine Description:
4563 //
4564 // This routine is called to acquire the remove lock for a device object.
4565 // While the lock is held, the caller can assume that no pending pnp REMOVE
4566 // requests will be completed.
4567 //
4568 // The lock should be acquired immediately upon entering a dispatch routine.
4569 // It should also be acquired before creating any new reference to the
4570 // device object if there's a chance of releasing the reference before the
4571 // new one is done, in addition to references to the driver code itself,
4572 // which is removed from memory when the last device object goes.
4573 //
4574 // Arguments:
4575 //
4576 // RemoveLock - A pointer to an initialized REMOVE_LOCK structure.
4577 //
4578 // Tag - Used for tracking lock allocation and release. The same tag
4579 // specified when acquiring the lock must be used to release the lock.
4580 // Tags are only checked in checked versions of the driver.
4581 //
4582 // File - set to __FILE__ as the location in the code where the lock was taken.
4583 //
4584 // Line - set to __LINE__.
4585 //
4586 // Return Value:
4587 //
4588 // Returns whether or not the remove lock was obtained.
4589 // If successful the caller should continue with work calling
4590 // IoReleaseRemoveLock when finished.
4591 //
4592 // If not successful the lock was not obtained. The caller should abort the
4593 // work but not call IoReleaseRemoveLock.
4594 //
4595 
4596 #define IoReleaseRemoveLock(RemoveLock, Tag) \
4597  IoReleaseRemoveLockEx(RemoveLock, Tag, sizeof (IO_REMOVE_LOCK))
4598 
4599 NTKERNELAPI
4600 VOID
4601 NTAPI
4602 IoReleaseRemoveLockEx(
4603  IN PIO_REMOVE_LOCK RemoveLock,
4604  IN PVOID Tag, // Optional
4605  IN ULONG RemlockSize // are we checked or free
4606  );
4607 //
4608 //
4609 // Routine Description:
4610 //
4611 // This routine is called to release the remove lock on the device object. It
4612 // must be called when finished using a previously locked reference to the
4613 // device object. If an Tag was specified when acquiring the lock then the
4614 // same Tag must be specified when releasing the lock.
4615 //
4616 // When the lock count reduces to zero, this routine will signal the waiting
4617 // event to release the waiting thread deleting the device object protected
4618 // by this lock.
4619 //
4620 // Arguments:
4621 //
4622 // DeviceObject - the device object to lock
4623 //
4624 // Tag - The TAG (if any) specified when acquiring the lock. This is used
4625 // for lock tracking purposes
4626 //
4627 // Return Value:
4628 //
4629 // none
4630 //
4631 
4632 #define IoReleaseRemoveLockAndWait(RemoveLock, Tag) \
4633  IoReleaseRemoveLockAndWaitEx(RemoveLock, Tag, sizeof (IO_REMOVE_LOCK))

5482 // Cancel SAFE API set start
5483 //
5484 // The following APIs are to help ease the pain of writing queue packages that
5485 // handle the cancellation race well. The idea of this set of APIs is to not
5486 // force a single queue data structure but allow the cancel logic to be hidden
5487 // from the drivers. A driver implements a queue and as part of its header
5488 // includes the IO_CSQ structure. In its initialization routine it calls
5489 // IoInitializeCsq. Then in the dispatch routine when the driver wants to
5490 // insert an IRP into the queue it calls IoCsqInsertIrp. When the driver wants
5491 // to remove something from the queue it calls IoCsqRemoveIrp. Note that Insert
5492 // can fail if the IRP was cancelled in the meantime. Remove can also fail if
5493 // the IRP was already cancelled.
5494 //
5495 // There are typically two modes where drivers queue IRPs. These two modes are
5496 // covered by the cancel safe queue API set.
5497 //
5498 // Mode 1:
5499 // One is where the driver queues the IRP and at some later
5500 // point in time dequeues an IRP and issues the IO request.
5501 // For this mode the driver should use IoCsqInsertIrp and IoCsqRemoveNextIrp.
5502 // The driver in this case is expected to pass NULL to the irp context
5503 // parameter in IoInsertIrp.
5504 //
5505 // Mode 2:
5506 // In this the driver queues the IRP, issues the IO request (like issuing a DMA
5507 // request or writing to a register) and when the IO request completes (either
5508 // using a DPC or timer) the driver dequeues the IRP and completes it. For this
5509 // mode the driver should use IoCsqInsertIrp and IoCsqRemoveIrp. In this case
5510 // the driver should allocate an IRP context and pass it in to IoCsqInsertIrp.
5511 // The cancel API code creates an association between the IRP and the context
5512 // and thus ensures that when the time comes to remove the IRP it can ascertain
5513 // correctly.
5514 //
5515 // Note that the cancel API set assumes that the field DriverContext[3] is
5516 // always available for use and that the driver does not use it.
5517 //
5518 
5519 
5520 //
5521 // Bookkeeping structure. This should be opaque to drivers.
5522 // Drivers typically include this as part of their queue headers.
5523 // Given a CSQ pointer the driver should be able to get its
5524 // queue header using CONTAINING_RECORD macro
5525 //
5526 
5527 typedef struct _IO_CSQ IO_CSQ, *PIO_CSQ;
